tures and thin shapes of things ineessantly stream from their surface. Therefore many idols are begotten in a short time, so that the birth of such things is with good reason named a rapid one. And as the sun must send forth many rays of light in a short time in order that all things may be continually filled with it, so also for a like reason there must be carried away from things in a moment of time idols of things many in number in many ways in all directions round 3 since to whatever part of them we present a mirror before their surfaceS, other things cor- respond to these in the mirror of a like shape and like colour.

Moreover though the state of heaven has just before been of unsullied purity, with exceeding suddenness it becomes so hideously overcast, that you might imagine all its darkness had abandoned Acheron throughout and filled up the great vaults of heaven: in such numbers, mid the frightful night of stom-clouds that has gathered, do faces of black horrour hang over us on high. Now there is no one who can tell how small a fraction of these an image is, or express that sum in language.
